7633.englishDescription: Russian Poker is a variation of Caribbean Stud Poker. The player's goal is to beat the dealer's hand. Initially, the player places a bet called Ante. The player can benefit from exchanging any number of cards or buying an extra card. Even if the dealer's hand doesn't qualify, the player can buy his qualification! So much for the rules, let's play!

7632.englishDescription: Pontoon is considered to be an early variation of the original Blackjack game played nowadays. The game is played with 8 regular decks against the 4 decks used in the original Blackjack. The goal is to come as close to 21 without going over, while still having a higher total than the Dealer as in a standard Blackjack game. In Pontoon any five-card hand (not busted) or a "pontoon" (the same as "blackjack" hand) pays 2 to 1, including after splitting. Re-splitting is available (up to 3 hands in total). However there is no dealer up card and the dealer wins on ties.

7631.englishDescription: Pai Gow Poker is "the marriage" between Pai Gow, a Chinese game of dominoes, and a 7-card Stud Poker. The simple basic strategy for setting your hand is to make the highest 2-card hand that is less than your 5-card hand.

7377.englishDescription: Red Dog is an exciting game from the old West played with three cards. Red Dog does not really resemble any other form of poker; it is simply three cards dealt with the player betting on the spread. Also known as Between the Sheets, Red Dog is built around the concept of the spread between two cards. Players are dealt two cards and place bets on whether they think the third card's value will fall between the original two. Red Dog Progressive is a famous table game, pulling the player in with that old promise: a lucky draw can turn a broken man into a winner.
